{"text": "the Hamiltonian takes the form\n\nH\n\n\u2248\n\nNK\n\n2\n\n\u00141\n\n2u(cos \u03b8)2 \u2212\u03b5 cos \u03b8 \u2212sin \u03b8 cos \u03c6\n\n\u0015\n\n(37.8)\n\n184\n\nwhere the scaled parameters are\n\nu \u2261NU\n\nK ,\n\n\u03b5 \u2261E\n\nK\n\n(37.9)\n\nWe can describe phase space using the canonical coordinates (\u03c6, n), so the total area of phase space is 2\u03c0N and\n\nPlanck cell is 2\u03c0\u0127with \u0127= 1. Optionally we can use spherical coordinates (\u03c6, \u03b8), so the total area of phase space\n\nis 4\u03c0 and Planck cell 4\u03c0/N. Note that an area element in phase space can be written as d\u03c6d cos \u03b8.\n\nWithin the framework of the semiclassical picture a quantum state is described as a distribution in phase space, and\n\nthe eigenstates are associated with strips that are stretched along contour lines H(\u03c6, \u03b8) = E of the Hamiltonian. The n\u27e9states are the eigenstates of the K = 0 Hamiltonian. In particular the n=N\u27e9state (all the particles are in the\n\nfirst site) is a Gaussian-like wavepacket which is concentrated in the NorthPole. By rotation we get from it a family\n\nof states \u03b8, \u03c6\u27e9that are called coherent states. If U is large, E = 0, and K is very small, then the eigenstates are the\n\nsymmetric and the antisymmetric superpositions of the \u00b1 n\u27e9states. In particular we have \u201dcat states\u201d of the type: CatState\u27e9\n\n= n1=N, n2=0\u27e9\n\n+\n\neiphase n1=0, n2=N\u27e9\n\n(37.10)\n\nIf a coherent state evolves, then the non-linearity (for non zero U) will stretch it.\n\nSometimes the evolved state\n\nmight resemble a cat state. We can characterize the one-body coherence of a state by defining the one-body reduced\n\nprobability matrix as\n\n\u03c1(1)\n\nji\n\n=\n\n1\n\nN \u27e8\u02c6a\u2020\n\ni\u02c6aj\u27e9\n\n=\n\n1\n\n2(1 + S \u00b7 \u03c3)\n\n(37.11)\n\nwhere Si = (2/N)\u27e8Ji\u27e9, and the so called polarization vector is S = (Sx, Sy, Sz). Note that\n\nAverageOccupation = (N/2) [1 + Sz]\n\n(37.12)\n\nOneBodyPurity = (1/2)\n\n\u0002\n\n1 + S2\n\nx + S2\n\ny + S2\n\nz\n\n\u0003\n\n(37.13)\n\nThe coherent states have maximum OneBodyPurity. This purity can be diminished due to non-linear effects or due to\n\ninteraction with environmental degrees of freedom.", "embedding": [0.015372187, -0.031170813, 0.06956754, -0.028399652, 1.8510821e-06, -0.00076858833, -0.013687788, -0.023451412, -0.054318402, 0.05832408, 0.062332015, 0.004344919, -0.035346683, -0.005095665, -0.008771791, 0.016452324, -0.0050299107, -0.018188745, -0.09760276, 0.0013964684, 0.031551797, 0.012816058, -0.08639992, -0.020395797, -0.033781487, 0.04642476, 0.027072104, 0.0643912, 0.047905352, 0.014831331, 0.04768705, -0.03783188, 0.012117633, -0.06752645, -0.0073478017, 0.0042112484, 0.028007705, -0.016750757, 0.023279093, -0.025525566, 0.044677414, -0.023853462, 0.0060331444, -0.043727, -0.021106921, 0.0046115634, -0.020730417, 0.005035203, 0.0073219547, -0.0580525, 0.0066478024, 0.019835332, 0.04019621, -0.055648718, -0.018403286, -0.01821619, -0.0025138378, 0.02912324, -0.028295089, 0.029363591, 0.05568257, 0.028757138, -0.0028970423, -0.05294345, -0.014264265, 0.06648205, -0.0051392145, 0.0385246, 0.012929672, -0.045964867, 0.0005653007, -0.016384266, -0.015810667, 0.012574526, -0.05247776, 0.037626956, -0.02055776, -0.017946238, -0.021230098, -0.027971655, 0.013590419, -0.025217455, -0.01260814, -0.0017448566, -0.014933894, 0.0021885869, -0.017708587, -0.0077462103, 0.031206308, 0.020345274, 0.03474545, 0.06814166, 0.0044905986, -0.01323148, 0.047404997, 0.033340152, 0.01787002, 0.017770803, 0.053590972, 0.049566757, -0.006658436, 0.03536917, -0.028265491, 0.059769005, -0.041157532, 0.046771664, -0.0037720755, 0.053163003, -0.000879774, -0.02465129, 0.010044507, -0.0030326417, 0.006187741, 0.024758406, 0.0023744232, 0.025792655, 0.015597982, 0.008554514, -0.013139899, -0.02226335, -0.008885594, 0.009257187, 0.018304937, 0.028412662, 0.02346457, -0.007652